It's a cultural thing, we like glitz and glamour. My village from Palestine throw parties like they're the Oscars. You have to buy or make a gown, and it can only be worn once. We have 3 different parties just for an engagement (Qirayit Fatiha, Tulba, Khutba), then we have the Love Story which needs to be photographed & filmed, then we have the Bridal Shower and Bachelorette Party (we do both), then we have the Family Gathering & you can't diss anyone by not inviting them so you need to rent out a huge dining hall, then you have the party after visiting the Courthouse & Mosque (Haflat Kitaba), then the Goodbye Ceremony the night before the Henna & you can't diss anyone so you need to rent a cabin, then you have the huge Henna Party where everyone needs to come in traditional thobe dresses decked out in gems & Swarovski crystals, wear their 100 gold coin headdress, and all the gold they own around their necks, fingers, and arms. At last, you then have the White Wedding. I'm no longer part of that extravagant and overindulgent culture (I'm Atheist now), but it was very glamorous and there was always 2 to 3 parties a week every year. During my 1st engagement, I had anxiety over throwing so many parties. It's overwhelming. If you want to make money, buy a party center or dining hall near an Arab population -- you'll be booked for the rest of your life! Arabs love to celebrate everything! Have a baby? Graduate college? Family reunion? Is it a holiday? Just want to throw a fair or carnival for the hell of it? Bouncy Castle operators, Photographers, Seamstresses, and Wedding Singers are able to send their kids to college and travel every year, bc of our Arab lifestyle.

I love looking at this stuff! I think if you saw my wardrobe you would die on the spot because it's so practical. It's different than most peeps because of my body shape, which lead me years ago to making certain parts of what I wear. If it goes on over the waist, you can bet I made it, custom for myself. This includes my sweaters and coats knittingart.net if you're interested. It also includes shirts as I have worked out a system for dressing. Easy, moderately colorful and practical. Corduroy pants, straight legs in an array of solids. Depending on the season, I wear 3/4 sleeve length t-shirts, solid colors in a completely different size range than the pants. Are we painting a pic yet? After that, it's up to me. My fabric comes from either Liberty of London or from Balinese artisans who make batik pint cotton fabrics. Did I mention being a natural fiber snob? My wool for knitting comes from all over the globe but I purchase them either from the wholesaler because of my business, Knitting Art, or from the internet, believe it or not, Ebay sells yarn from outlets in Germany that are all up to date colors and fibers at wholesale prices. This still makes one sweater sell for minimum of $350, charging $1/hour for labor. The buying public just doesn't want to pay real prices for real labor. I do it because I love it and because I personally need clothing. As for shoes, I was a ballerina many years ago and then a Registered Nurse, and contracted arthritis when I was 18 years old. Birkenstocks to the rescue! my feet are too deformed (I told you my body has weird problems) to wear closed toe shoes which is just fine with me. It's so easy to pull a look together. Do I feel pink today? How about Drama Queen? I also have some vintage things I bought 30 years ago that will remain classics: silk blouse with puff sleeves and button down in ecru. Basic. Chenille skirt in olive green with fringe at the bottom. Business outfit. Put a silk jacket that has been heavily worked with embroidery and patches of velvet in a deep teal with the blouse and skirt and there you have it. Flowers in the hair, eelskin bag and done. Simple. Formal wear, totally different story. I do my own because of the fitting problems. I do a lot of beads and hand made lace on silk and velvet in conservative colors, dark raspberry, navy, slate gray silk chiffon pants topped with a tulle jacket decorated with satin ribbon in teal and brown with a pale shade blouse and a nice strand of pearls matching earrings and it's time to go to a wedding. I just ordered some fabulous silk from a wholesaler I know for $40, 3 yards for a skirt. I made a silk top that feels lonely. It's in dupioni with amber/rose tints, solid color and the new fabric will compliment, over a full petticoat. It's practical, not expensive and I feel great wearing it. Enough said.
